nt-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> savings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are pass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on to motorists and not simply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> achieved to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> improv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> shareholder return. This should be addressed through legislation. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The industry cites insurance fraud as a key driver of premium cost and the Government has responded by recommending that medical experts be accredited to improve the quality of reporting a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd reduce the incidence of fraud. Done correctly, Slater &amp; Gordon support the accreditation of medical experts.  To succeed, a scheme must be completely independent and impartial from influence from interested parties. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If fraud does exist at a level which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">causing premium pressure, all stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">must do everything</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r power to limit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; f