ilable between insurance comp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anies and must be accessible to claimant lawyers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Claimant lawyers would then be armed with all the relevant information before </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advising clients whether or not to proceed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This would place a positive obligation on all parties to identify suspicion of fraud</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ulent behaviour and cease acting at the outset if necessary.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore making this information public is a matter of public safety as it could be used by the Highways Agency to target accident blackspots and analyse trends in the impacts of new roads a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd layouts. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Small claims limit</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Slater &amp; Gordon strongly supports the Transport Select Committee’s position on the small claims limit and its stance against the proposals put forward by the insurance industry. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The small claims court is not designed for pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ople who represent themselves in personal injury cases and raising the limit at any time in the future would create a significant barrier in some people right to access to justice. We do not believe that raising the limit would have any impact at all on ta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ckling fraud.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are therefore pleased that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Government has at this stage decided against </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">moving whiplash cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aims to the small claims court. It is vital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> claimants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">never </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lose the right to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal representation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> forced to resolve cases against</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a professional litigant, which would ultimately result in claims being under-settled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and  shift the cost of treatment to the NHS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0p